{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522236"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:42:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13815"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13815"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.14,0.55,0.08,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51236"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6432"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13815"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36515"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"},{"type":"tags","id":"1218"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14028"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51236"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with painful ulcers on both legs that have rapidly progressed over the past two weeks. On examination, he appears in extreme discomfort with a heart rate of 105. Examination of his legs reveals multiple deep ulcers with undermined, violaceous borders and a necrotic base (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is most likely to be associated with this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Renal transplant","Venous congestion","Ulcerative colitis","Diabetes mellitus","Peripheral arterial disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described in the stem and seen in the image is highly suggestive of pyoderma gangrenosum, a neutrophilic dermatosis characterized by painful, rapidly progressing ulcers with violaceous, undermined borders. These lesions typically occur on the legs, as seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcerative colitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer and the condition most commonly associated with pyoderma gangrenosum. Approximately 50% of patients with pyoderma gangrenosum have underlying inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), with ulcerative colitis being more common than Crohn\u0027s disease. The skin lesions may precede, coincide with, or follow the onset of IBD symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous congestion\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to venous ulcers, but these typically have a more gradual onset, are less painful, and have different characteristics compared to pyoderma gangrenosum. Venous ulcers usually have irregular borders, are shallow, and are associated with other signs of venous insufficiency such as varicose veins and hemosiderin deposition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal transplant\u003C/strong\u003E recipients can develop various skin complications, but pyoderma gangrenosum is not specifically associated with renal transplantation. Post-transplant skin issues are more commonly related to immunosuppression, such as increased risk of skin cancers or opportunistic infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral arterial disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause ischemic ulcers, but these are typically more common in older individuals with risk factors for atherosclerosis. Ischemic ulcers are usually extremely painful, have a punched-out appearance, and are associated with absent or diminished peripheral pulses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with various types of ulcers, particularly neuropathic ulcers on pressure points of the feet. However, diabetic ulcers do not typically present with the rapid progression and characteristic appearance of pyoderma gangrenosum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while ulcerative colitis is the most likely associated condition, pyoderma gangrenosum can also be associated with other systemic diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis, hematological disorders, or can occur in isolation. A thorough workup is necessary to identify any underlying conditions and guide appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pyoderma gangrenosum is often associated with inflammatory bowel disease, particularly ulcerative colitis.","Pyoderma gangrenosum presents as painful, rapidly progressing ulcers with violaceous borders, typically on the legs.","Differential diagnosis of pyoderma gangrenosum includes venous ulcers, vasculitis, and infection."],"references":["Brooklyn T, Dunnill G, Probert C. Diagnosis and treatment of pyoderma gangrenosum. BMJ. 2006 Jul 22;333(7560):181-4. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1513476/","Hwang S, Fernandez-Penas. Pyoderma gangrenosum. The Australasian College of Dermatologists. 2015. Available at: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/pyoderma-gangrenosum/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36515"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13815"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20761"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20761"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg